HDR
Motivation
  • Up to now, all color output has been in 0…1 range
    • Low Dynamic Range lighting (LDR)
  • But: Inadequate to capture realistic scenes
    • Ex: Imagine outdoors on a sunny day
    • Sun is millions of times brighter than shadows
    • LDR can’t capture this range
HDR
  • HDR = High Dynamic Range
  • We allow any values to be output from FS
  • We also allow light color to be larger than 1
  • Usually, hardware clamps FS output to 0…1 range
  • But: If we use floating point FBO, this does not happen
HDR
  • Floating point FBO: Not supported on all platforms (mobiles)
    • But on desktops, we almost always have it available
  • Create Framebuffer: Framebuffer fbo{w,h,1, GL_RGBA16F};
    • 16 bits per pixel
    • Floating point format
  • Drawback: 8 bytes per pixel (instead of 4, as in RGBA8)

  • Example of the effects we can get: Here, light value is multiplied by 10 when computing specular highlights
Example
  • Here, emission is scaled too
  • Notice halo overlaps red sphere
Example
  • Combining glow/bloom with HDR: Blur radius = 19; blur shader multiplies its final output by 2
  • Left: LDR. Right: HDR. Notice: More bloom
Example
  • Suppose we’re drawing an outdoor scene at noon
  • We set light to [10,10,10] and use that everywhere
  • What do we get? Washed out scene!
  • Why doesn’t the world look washed out in real life?
Explanation
  • Human visual system:
    • Dark adaptation (visual purple)
      • 30 minutes!
    • Pupil opens and closes
  • We should simulate these effects to get realism
Tone Mapping
  • Tone mapping: Process of remapping HDR values (0…∞) into LDR (0..1) range
  • Simplest: Linear tone mapping: Just scale
  • Ex: At end of FS:
    color.rgb = clamp(color.rgb, minValue, maxValue ); color.rgb = (color.rgb-minValue) / (maxValue-minValue)
  • Ex: Maybe minValue = 0.5, maxValue = 5.0
Analysis
  • Linear tone mapping is OK as a first step
  • But it eliminates most of the HDR-ness of HDR
    • Maybe better results from S-shaped remapping
  • Also: How do we know what the values should be in the clamp() and the division?
    • The 0.5 and 5.0 given previously are more-or-less arbitrary
Analysis
  • Another issue: Color shift
  • Suppose we have a pixel that is (45.5, 9.5, 0)
    • A very bright reddish orange
  • After remapping, we get (10,2,0)
    • Still a very reddish orange
  • When we output, everything gets clamped to 0…1 range
    • So we get (1,1,0) → Yellow.
  • Oops.
Analysis
  • Color shift occurs because our remapped color gets clamped
    • We lose the difference between red and green when both go over 1.0
  • Better way: Adaptive exposure determination
    • Simulate human eye: Pupil opens wider in darker environment
Illumination
  • Interesting Fact: Moon’s surface is same reflectivity as asphalt
    • But a full moon appears much brighter than that
    • Why? Eye adjusts its sensitivity range upward when it’s dark
  • We need to determine average brightness of scene, use that to set low/high cutoffs
Illumination
  • We already have the information
  • Recall how mipmaps worked…
    • Highest mip level holds average of entire scene
Procedure
  • At setup time:
    • Create floating point FBO. Same size as window.
  • In draw():
    • Render scene to FP FBO
    • Activate tone mapping shader (next slides)
    • Use FP FBO as input texture
    • Draw quad
      • Result goes to screen.
Shaders
  • VS is just identity shader
  • We’ve seen this before, so no need to repeat it again
Shaders
  • Fragment shader looks like so:
layout(binding=0) uniform sampler2D tex;
in vec2 v_texCoord;
out vec4 color;
void main(){
    //force sample from highest mip level: bias=100
    //my GPU had a bug where passing constant texture coordinate
    //always gives mip level zero
    vec3 avgBrightness = texture( tex, vec3(v_texCoord,0), 100 );
    color = texture( tex, vec3( v_texCoord, 0.0 ) );
    ...use avgBrightness to remap color...
}
Color Space
  • We can address the color-shift problem by using a different color space
  • What is a color space?
RGB
  • Usually we use RGB (Red/Green/Blue): An additive color model
  • Corresponds roughly to human eye perception
  • Three types of color photoreceptors (cones) + black/white receptors (rods)
CMYK
  • Print color cannot use RGB
  • Inks don’t emit light; Can only reflect
  • So we use a subtractive model: CMY (Cyan/Magenta/Yellow)
  • Since most inks aren’t perfect absorbers, mixing CMY gives a muddy dark olive color
  • Plus: Expensive: So printers use CMYK (CMY + Black)
HSV
  • Hue/Saturation/Value
  • Hue = What color (red, orange, yellow, green, blue, magenta)
  • Saturation = How pastel or vibrant?
  • Value = How light or dark?
YUV
  • Original televisions: Black and white
  • Only the luminance was transmitted
  • Color TV: Needed to maintain compatibility
  • Color encoding: YUV
    • Y = luminance channel: Black and white TV’s only see this
      • Take weighted average of RGB: Y = w1R + w2G + w3B
    • U,V = chrominance channels
      • Let U = R - Y
      • Let V = B - Y
  • To reverse it:
    • R = Y+U
    • B = Y+V
    • G = (Y − w1R − w3B)/(w2)
YCbCr
  • YCbCr: Used for DVDs (MPEG video) and JPEGs
  • Basically the same as YUV but with some scaling and offset
XYZ
  • CIE (International Commission of Lighting) defined three primaries X,Y,Z
    • Any color which humans can see can be defined as weighted combination of XYZ
    • Weights are always positive
    • X,Y,Z don’t correspond to any wavelength of light, so we can’t visualize them directly
Conversion
  • To convert RGB to XYZ:
    • X = 0.4124564*r + 0.3575761*g + 0.1804375*b
    • Y = 0.2126729*r + 0.7151522*g + 0.0721750*b
    • Z = 0.0193339*r + 0.1191920*g + 0.9503041*b
  • To convert XYZ to RGB:
    • r = 3.2404542*X + -1.5371385*Y + -0.4985314*Z
    • g = -0.969266*X + 1.8760108*Y + 0.0415560*Z
    • b = 0.0556434*X + -0.204259*Y + 1.0572252*Z
xyY
  • Related to XYZ
  • Y = luminance. Taken directly from XYZ’s Y value
  • x = (X)/(X + Y + Z)
  • y = (Y)/(X + Y + Z)
  • x and y encode chrominance
  • So we have luminance and chrominance cleanly separated
    • Note: If we have black (X=Y=Z=0) then we need to pick arbitrary value for x and y
  • Convert xyY to XYZ:
    • X = (Yx)/(y)
    • Z = (Y(1 − x − y))/(y)
Procedure
  • So: How does any of this help us?
    • Render scene to FBO.
    • Output xyY, not RGB, from FS
      • Convert RGB → xyY
  • When done: Use highest mipmap level to get Y (luminance)
  • Set scaling based on luminance value
  • Then: Render FBO to screen
    • Scale luminance (Y)
    • Convert back to RGB at the last second before outputting
